{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598136"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.92,0.02,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8136"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8761"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19721"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gut microbiome consists of a multitude of microorganisms residing in the gastrointestinal tract. It plays a crucial role in digestion, immune function, and overall health. Various factors can influence the composition and function of the gut microbiome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding the gut microbiome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Babies born via C-section are rapidly colonised with maternal faecal organisms","Antibiotic administration has been associated with changes in the gut microbiota","The mechanisms driving recurrent post-dieting obesity are well-understood","The gut microbiome is identical in all individuals","Diet has no impact on the gut microbiome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotic administration has been associated with changes in the gut microbiota\u003C/strong\u003E. Antibiotics can disrupt the gut microbial balance, leading to changes in the microbiome composition. This can affect digestion, immune function, and overall health. \u003Cstrong\u003EBabies born via C-section\u003C/strong\u003E are not rapidly colonised with maternal faecal organisms; instead, they are more likely to be colonised by skin and environmental bacteria. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emechanisms driving recurrent post-dieting obesity\u003C/strong\u003E are not yet fully understood. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egut microbiome is not identical\u003C/strong\u003E in all individuals; it varies based on genetics, diet, environment, and other factors. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiet\u003C/strong\u003E does have a significant impact on the gut microbiome, influencing its composition and function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gut microbiome is influenced by various factors, including antibiotic use.","Antibiotic administration can cause changes in the composition of the gut microbiota.","The gut microbiome plays a significant role in immune system function and overall health."],"references":["Sorboni SG, Moghaddam HS, Jafarzadeh-Esfehani R, Soleimanpour S. A Comprehensive Review on the Role of the Gut Microbiome in Human Neurological Disorders. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2022 Jan 19;35(1):e0033820. doi: 10.1128/CMR.00338-20. Epub 2022 Jan 5. PMID: 34985325; PMCID: PMC8729913.","de Vos WM, Tilg H, Van Hul M, Cani PD. Gut microbiome and health: mechanistic insights. Gut. 2022 May;71(5):1020-1032. doi: 10.1136/gutjnl-2021-326789. Epub 2022 Feb 1. PMID: 35105664; PMCID: PMC8995832.","Al Bander Z, Nitert MD, Mousa A, Naderpoor N. The Gut Microbiota and Inflammation: An Overview. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2020 Oct 19;17(20):7618. doi: 10.3390/ijerph17207618. PMID: 33086688; PMCID: PMC7589951."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T23:06:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T23:06:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8136"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading